### Functional Explanation
The objective is to write an automated verification testbench component that monitors a synchronous FIFO. A correctly designed FIFO should never assert both `full` and `empty` at the exact same time.

### Potential Issues
No issues with the instruction. The requested output is a SystemVerilog/Verilog testbench constraint.

### Recommended Fix
Using standard Verilog `$error` tasks or SystemVerilog `assert property` for continuous monitoring:
```systemverilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module tb_fifo_monitor;
  reg clk, rst;
  wire empty, full;
  // ... FIFO instantiation here ...

  // Generate clock
  initial clk = 0;
  always #5 clk = ~clk;

  // Method 1: Verilog always block monitoring
  always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (!rst) begin
      if (empty === 1'b1 && full === 1'b1) begin
        $error("[%0t] FATAL ERROR: FIFO asserted both empty and full!", $time);
        $finish;
      end
    end
  end

  // Method 2: SystemVerilog Concurrent Assertion
  property never_empty_and_full;
    @(posedge clk) disable iff (rst)
    not (empty && full);
  endproperty

  assert property (never_empty_and_full) else 
    $error("[%0t] SVA Failure: FIFO is simultaneously empty and full!", $time);

endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
Assertions are strictly for simulation and formal verification tools. Synthesis tools (like Vivado or Quartus) use `translate_off / translate_on` pragmas to ignore these constructs, though modern tools automatically skip `assert` statements. Ensure `disable iff (rst)` is used so the assertion does not fire during asynchronous pipeline initialization when values are `X`.

