### Functional Explanation
In a testbench, generating multiple clocks with a specific frequency and integer multiple relationship (like 100MHz and 25MHz) requires careful manipulation of delays to ensure their rising edges align synchronously, emulating the behavior of an FPGA PLL/MMCM.

### Potential Issues
There are no bugs to fix; the request is for testbench generation logic.

### Recommended Fix
100 MHz means a period of 10ns (5ns high, 5ns low). 25 MHz means a period of 40ns (20ns high, 20ns low). To keep them edge-aligned, start them at the same time and toggle them at their respective half-periods.
```systemverilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module tb_clocks;
  reg clk_100mhz = 0;
  reg clk_25mhz = 0;

  // 100MHz Clock Generation: T=10ns (Toggle every 5ns)
  always #5.0 clk_100mhz = ~clk_100mhz;

  // 25MHz Clock Generation: T=40ns (Toggle every 20ns)
  always #20.0 clk_25mhz = ~clk_25mhz;

  initial begin
    $dumpfile("clocks.vcd");
    $dumpvars(0, tb_clocks);
    #200; // Run for 200ns
    $finish;
  end
endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
Since `initial` and `#` delay variables are non-synthesizable, this is strictly for simulation. For actual hardware, you would instantiate an MMCM/PLL IP core (e.g., Xilinx `MMCME2_ADV`) and drive a single input clock, extracting the 100MHz and 25MHz from the `CLKOUT` ports to guarantee phase alignment and minimize clock skew across the global clock routing network.

